</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC26A7DFA91954D18B7B898" pageId="57" pageNumber="815" type="activity">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC26A7DFA91954D18B7B898" blockId="57.[1389,2598,275,1255]" pageId="57" pageNumber="815">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC26A7DFA91954D185DB807" bold="true" box="[1389,1629,788,821]" pageId="57" pageNumber="815">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Kirindy Pipistrelles are nocturnal. Search-call shape is a steep FM sweep with start frequencies of 69-120-6 kHz, end frequencies 28-46-8 kHz, peak frequencies 49-3-51-2 kHz, durations 1-9—4-6 milliseconds, and interpulse intervals 19-8-70-2 milliseconds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC26A7DFA9395E8171CB8E0" box="[1391,2332,945,978]" pageId="57" pageNumber="815" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC26A7DFA9395E8171CB8E0" blockId="57.[1389,2598,275,1255]" box="[1391,2332,945,978]" pageId="57" pageNumber="815">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC26A7DFA9395E8162DB8E0" bold="true" box="[1391,2093,945,978]" pageId="57" pageNumber="815">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8C8E6575FFC26A7DFA8C958016AFBFA5" pageId="57" pageNumber="815" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="C42B36FEFFC26A7DFA8C958016AFBFA5" blockId="57.[1389,2598,275,1255]" pageId="57" pageNumber="815">
<emphasis id="F6E0EAECFFC26A7DFA8C958018DBB8C8" bold="true" box="[1392,1755,985,1018]" pageId="57" pageNumber="815">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List. The Kirindy Pipistrelle is currently known only from a few localities, but appears to be relatively common throughoutits range, based on capture frequency. The species is found in human-altered areas, indicating some degree of resilience. However,it might be threatened by forest clearing for agricultural expansion.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
